/-!
  ## 1.34 Definitions

  If P and Q are partially ordered sets, a map œÜ : P ‚Üí Q is "order preserving" or
  "monotone" if and only if `‚àÄ (x y : P), x ‚â§ y ‚Üí œÜ x ‚â§ œÜ y`. In Lean, this is
  written as `Monotone œÜ`. Lean also has `MonotoneOn œÜ s` to mean
  `‚àÄ x ‚àà s, ‚àÄ y ‚àà s, x ‚â§ y ‚Üí œÜ x ‚â§ œÜ y`. Lean also has a "bundled" type
  called `OrderHom` that consists of a function together with the proof that
  it is monotone. The type of monotone maps from P to Q is also denoted `P ‚Üío Q`.

  The map œÜ is called an "order embedding" if it satisfies
  `‚àÄ x y : P, x ‚â§ y ‚Üî œÜ x ‚â§ œÜ y`. Lean offers a bundled type called `orderEmbedding P Q`
  that consists of

  (i) a function f

  (ii) a proof that f is injective

  (iii) a proof that the order embedding property is satisfied

  We already saw above in 1.4 that map betwee partial orders that satisfies (iii)
  also satisfies (ii). We called this `injective_of_le_iff_le`. But order embeddings can be
  defined assuming only that `‚â§` is defined, so the structure asks for a proof of
  injectivity. The type of order embeddings from P to Q is denoted `P ‚Ü™o Q`

  TODO: Figure out if we need to specify injectivity for an order embedding between
  `PartialOrder`s.
-/

